06038nam a2200805Ia 9781487548346DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20232023onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875483467 a10.3138/97814875483462doi  a(DE-B1597)651152  a(OCoLC)1331149286  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a305.896/0712231 aHoward, Philip S.S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPerforming Postracialism :bReflections on Antiblackness, Nation, and Education through Contemporary Blackface in Canada /cPhilip S.S. Howard. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Genesis and Intentions -- tPart One: Blackface in the Context of the Canadian Settler-Colonial Nation State -- t1. Contemporary Blackface in Canada as Performance of Antiblackness -- t2. What's the Joke? The Black Body as White Pleasure in Canadian Blackface -- t3. Defending Blackface: Performing the "Progressive," Postracialist Canadian -- t4. Pornotroping Performances: Overt Violence, Un/Gendering, and Sex in Contemporary Blackface -- tPart Two: Blackface in Education Contexts in Canada -- t5. Blackface at University: The Antiblack Logics of Canadian Academia -- t6. "Making Them Better Leaders": The Pedagogical Imperative, Institutional Priorities, and the Attenuation of Black Anger -- t7. Learning to Get Along at School, or Antiblack Postracialism through Multicultural Education -- t8. The Costs of Belonging for International Students -- t9. Fugitive Learning: Countering Postracialism and Making Black Life at University -- tReferences -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aBlackface - instances in which non-Black persons temporarily darken their skin with make-up to impersonate Black people, usually for fun, and frequently in educational contexts - constitutes a postracialist pedagogy that propagates antiblack logics. In Performing Postracialism, Philip S.S. Howard examines instances of contemporary blackface in Canada and argues that it is more than a simple matter of racial (mis)representation. The book looks at the ostensible humour and dominant conversations around blackface, arguing that they are manifestations of the particular formations of antiblackness in the Canadian nation state and its educational institutions. It posits that the occurrence of blackface in universities is not incidental, and outlines how educational institutions' responses to blackface in Canada rely upon a motivation to protect whiteness. Performing Postracialism draws from focus groups and individual interviews conducted with university students, faculty, administrators, and Black student associations, along with online articles about blackface, to provide the basis for a nuanced examination of the ways that blackface is experienced by Black persons. The book investigates the work done by Black students, faculty, and staff at universities to challenge blackface and the broader campus climate of antiblackness that generates it.  afunded by University of Toronto Libraries  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBlackfacezCanada. 0aCollege students, BlackzCanada. 0aRacism against Black peoplezCanada. 0aRacism in higher education. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh  aBlack studies.  aCanada.  aantiblackness/anti-Black racism.  ablackface.  ahigher education.  ahumour.  aminstrelsy.  apostracialism.  aracism.  asettler colonialism.2 aUniversity of Toronto